{{See|Freo}}
==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/fɹe:o/}}

===Etymology 1===
From Germanic ''*frija-'', from Indo-European ''*prāy-, *prēy-'' ‘like, love’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon ''frī-'' (in [[frilik|frīlik]]) (Dutch [[vrij]]), Old High German [[fri|frī]] (German [[frei]]), Gothic [[𐍆𐍂𐌴𐌹𐍃]]. The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πραυς]], Slavonic ''*prьjatī'' (Old Church Slavonic {{RUchar|[[прити]]}}, Russian [[приятель]] ‘friend’), Old Irish [[ríar]] (Welsh [[rhydd]] ‘free’).

====Adjective====
'''frēo'''
# [[free]], at [[liberty]]; [[exempt]]
#:''Beo he freo'': he shall be free.  (Alfred’s ''Laws'')
# ''(Poetic)'' [[noble]], [[glad]]
#:''Ða wearþ worn afeded freora bearna'': then a number of noble children were brought forth.  (Cædmon’s ''Metrical Paraphrase'')

====Related words====
*[[freond|frēond]]
*[[freogan|frēoġan]]
*[[friþ]]
*[[frig|frīġ]]

===Etymology 2===
From Germanic ''*fraw-'', a feminine form of ''*frauja-'' ‘lord’ (Old English [[frea|frēa]]), from Indo-European ''*prōw-'' ‘master, judge’. Cognate with Old Saxon [[frua|frūa]], Old High German [[frouwa]] (German [[Frau]]), Old Norse [[freyja]]. The IE root is also the source of Slavic ''*prāvъ'' (Old Church Slavonic [[правъ]], Russian [[правый]] ‘right’), and the first element of Latin [[provincia]].

====Noun====
'''frēo''' {{f}}
# a [[woman]]
#:''Oþ-ðæt he funde freo fægroste'': until he found the fairest woman. (Cædmon’s ''Metrical Paraphrase'')

